questions.text: All of the following is/are true regarding anatomy of the parotid gland except?

options.label: A
options.text: Stenson’s duct opens near 3rd molar tooth

options.label: B
options.text: Facial nerve divides it into superficial and deep parts

options.label: C
options.text: Deep lobecontains the deep lymph nodes

options.label: D
options.text: Traversed by retromandibular vein and facial artery

options.label: E
options.text: Auriculotemporal nerve is sensory to the parotid gland

questions.explanation:
Explanation:

  • • Option A: False. Parotid duct, also known as Stenson’s duct opens on the mucosa of inner cheek, opposite to the 2nd upper molar tooth (Not 3rd) Option B: True. The facial nerve divides the parotid gland into superficial and deep lobes. The lobes are joined by an isthmus of the glandular tissue. Option C: False. The deep lymph nodes are situated deep to the parotid capsule (not in the deep lobe). Remember that superficial lymph nodes are located in the superficial fascia.
  • • Option A: False. Parotid duct, also known as Stenson’s duct opens on the mucosa of inner cheek, opposite to the 2nd upper molar tooth (Not 3rd)
  • • Option B: True. The facial nerve divides the parotid gland into superficial and deep lobes. The lobes are joined by an isthmus of the glandular tissue.
  • • Option C: False. The deep lymph nodes are situated deep to the parotid capsule (not in the deep lobe). Remember that superficial lymph nodes are located in the superficial fascia.
  • • Option D: False. Facial artery does not traverse parotid gland, although retromandibular vein does. See the diagram (often repeated)
  • • Option E: True. Sensory supply to the parotid gland is derived from the auriculotemporal nerve, except for the parotid fascia and overlying skin, which are supplied by great auricular nerve (C2, C3).
  • • Option E: True. Sensory supply to the parotid gland is derived from the auriculotemporal nerve, except for the parotid fascia and overlying skin, which are supplied by great auricular nerve (C2, C3).
  • • Extra edge points about parotid gland
  • • Extra edge points about parotid gland
  • • Ectodermal origin Largest salivary gland Capsule formed by the investing layer of deep cervical fascia Parotid duct pierces buccinator muscle Parasympathetic nerves are secretomotor and reach via auriculotemporal nerve
  • • Ectodermal origin
  • • Largest salivary gland
  • • Capsule formed by the investing layer of deep cervical fascia
  • • Parotid duct pierces buccinator muscle
  • • Parasympathetic nerves are secretomotor and reach via auriculotemporal nerve
  • • The plane between superficial and deep lobe is called Patey’sfaciovenous plane and contains the nerves and veins, which has surgical relevance.

questions.text: Which among the following is/are true regarding anatomy of kidney?

options.label: A
options.text: The upper border corresponds to 1st lumbar vertebra and the lower border to 3rd lumbar vertebra

options.label: B
options.text: Lower Pole is lateral as compared to the upper pole

options.label: C
options.text: Supplied by preganglionic T8-T10 nerve fibers

options.label: D
options.text: Anterior segmental artery is part of arterial supply

options.label: E
options.text: Renal pyramid is the 1st part of the collecting system of kidneys

questions.explanation:
Explanation:

  • • Explanation:
  • • Option A: False. The upper pole of each kidney lies opposite T11 (Sometimes T12) and the lower pole lies opposite L3 vertebrae.
  • • Option A: False. The upper pole of each kidney lies opposite T11 (Sometimes T12) and the lower pole lies opposite L3 vertebrae.
  • • Option B: True. The upper pole of both the kidneys is slightly medial and posteriorly oriented as compared to the lower pole. Option C: False. Nerve supply comes from the renal plexus derived from celiac plexus and contains sympathetic fibres from T10-L1. Option D: True. Each renal artery is a branch of abdominal aorta and divides into anterior and posterior divisions. The anterior division further divides into segmental arteries (anterior: upper and middle as well as inferior). The segmental arteries give rise to interlobar branches, further forming arcuate branches, which eventually form interlobular branches.
  • • Option B: True. The upper pole of both the kidneys is slightly medial and posteriorly oriented as compared to the lower pole.
  • • Option C: False. Nerve supply comes from the renal plexus derived from celiac plexus and contains sympathetic fibres from T10-L1.
  • • Option D: True. Each renal artery is a branch of abdominal aorta and divides into anterior and posterior divisions. The anterior division further divides into segmental arteries (anterior: upper and middle as well as inferior). The segmental arteries give rise to interlobar branches, further forming arcuate branches, which eventually form interlobular branches.
  • • Option E: False. Collecting Tubules are the first structure to collect the urine and enter the pyramid as Ducts of Bellini.

questions.explanation:
Explanation:

  • • Explanation: Penile anatomy
  • • Arterial supply: From internal pudendal artery (a branch of anterior division of the internal iliac artery) Dorsal artery of penis: Run between corpora cavernosa; supply the fibrous tissue around corpora and skin of penis Deep artery of penis: Run within the corpora cavernosa after piercing the crura, thus supply the erectile tissue in the body of penis Artery to bulb of penis: Bulbo-urethral artery , supplies posterior part of the corpus spongiosum and the cowper’s glands. Penile skin is supplied by the superficial and deep branches of the external pudendal artery. Venous drainage: Three venous systems Superficial system: Eventually forms a single superficial dorsal vein which drains into the left saphenous vein Intermediate system: Contains the emissary veins which drain into circumflex veins and the deep dorsal veins Deep system: The crural and the cavernosal veins, which eventually drain into the internal pudendal vein.

Penile skin is supplied by the superficial and deep branches of the external pudendal artery.

  • • Suprascapular (branch of 1st part of subclavian). Deep branch of transverse cervical (branch of thyrocervical trunk from 1st part of subclavian). Circumflex scapular (branch of subscapular, which is a branch of 3rd part of axillary).
  • • Suprascapular (branch of 1st part of subclavian).
  • • Deep branch of transverse cervical (branch of thyrocervical trunk from 1st part of subclavian).
  • • Circumflex scapular (branch of subscapular, which is a branch of 3rd part of axillary).
  • • II. On the acromion process
  • • Acromial branch of thoraco-acromial (branch of 2nd part of axillary) artery. Ascending branch ofposterior circumflex humeral (branch of 3rd part of axillary). Acromial branch of suprascapular (branch of 1st part of subclavian).
  • • Acromial branch of thoraco-acromial (branch of 2nd part of axillary) artery.
  • • Ascending branch ofposterior circumflex humeral (branch of 3rd part of axillary).
  • • Acromial branch of suprascapular (branch of 1st part of subclavian).
  • • In other options, the arteries are not connecting the 1st part of subclavian with 3rd part of axillary artery.
